video_transcription: President-elect Donald Trump will be sentenced on January 10th. The Manhattan judge overseeing Trump's criminal prosecution today ordered him to appear either in person or virtually for sentencing next Friday. Trump was convicted in May of 34 felony counts of falsifying business records, about a 2016 hush money payment to porn actress Stormy Daniels. For more, let's bring in ABC News senior reporter Kathryn Falders live in West Palm Beach, Florida near Mar-a-Lago. So, Kathryn, what's the latest here? So this obviously comes as Trump's attorneys had filed a motion to have that hush money case in Manhattan dismissed. The judge rejected that and instead said that he must appear, Donald Trump must appear either in person or virtually to be sentenced on January 10th. That's only 10 days before his inauguration. But what the judge appears to indicate in this memo, in this decision, and this is important, he signals that he's intending to sentence Trump to what's called a quote unquote, unconditional discharge out of respect for the presidential immunity doctrine. We've been talking a lot about that presidential immunity decision at the Supreme Court. And the judge has said that he intends to sentence him to this unconditional discharge. Now what does that mean? It essentially means that Trump just gets off with a mark on his record. We've talked a lot about the potential for jail time or some other sort of sentence that is unlikely to happen here. And the judge essentially says as much, but it is big news that he will still be sentenced. He doesn't have to go in person. He can appear virtually. It's his decision and he will need to do that 10 days before he is inaugurated as next president.

But with Trump's limited government approach, could RFK's big food reforms hit a wall? The drama, RFK Jr. has made waves as an outspoken critic of processed foods and toxic ingredients, and he's got some ambitious plans if he becomes the Health and Human Services Secretary. Think rethinking school lunches, limiting sugar, and even revising the federal dietary guidelines that shape what we eat. But here's the kicker. Trump has promised RFK Jr. free reign to go wild on health, but does that clash with his own limited government stance? What's at stake? Could we see a major shift in how the US tackles nutrition, or will the food industry's heavy hitters stop him in his tracks? Here's the big question. video_transcription: Remember the story about the US presidential candidate who admitted to dumping a dead bear cub carcass in New York's Central Park? Well, Robert F. Kennedy Jr., who's since dropped out of the presidential race and has backed Donald Trump, allegedly also cut the head off a dead beach swell with a chainsaw and tied it to the roof of his car to take home. His daughter told the story, which likely happened around 1994, in a magazine interview back in 2012. She said that as they went down the highway, whale juice would pour into the windows of the car and it was the rankest thing on the planet. Adding, "...we all had plastic bags over our heads with mouth holes cut out. An environmental group which has backed Kamala Harris in the presidential race has called for an investigation. They claim he may have broken multiple federal laws by collecting wildlife body parts and transporting them across state lines. Mr. Kennedy has not commented on the incident and the BBC has approached his campaign for comment.

text: More than a dozen members of the Kennedy family formally endorsed President Biden, a rejection of their relative Robert F. Kennedy Jr., who is running for president as an independent candidate.   Kerry Kennedy ‚Äî the daughter of former Attorney General Robert F. Kennedy, niece of President John F. Kennedy and sister of RFK Jr. ‚Äî called President Biden her ‚Äúhero‚Äù as she rattled off a list of his accomplishments in office.   ‚ÄúWe want to make crystal clear our feeling that the best way forward for America is to reelect Joe Biden and Kamala Harris to four more years,‚Äù she said at the campaign event in Philadelphia on Thursday.   Prominent members of the Kennedy family have rejected RFK Jr.‚Äôs candidacy and disavowed some of his more controversial positions, particularly his anti-vaccine rhetoric.   Ms. Kennedy did not mention her brother by name but said ‚Äúthere are only two candidates with any chance of winning the presidency.‚Äù   RFK Jr. noted the endorsement on social media and said he is ‚Äúpleased‚Äù his relatives are politically active, calling it a ‚Äúfamily tradition.‚Äù   ‚ÄúWe are divided in our opinions but united in our love for each other,‚Äù he wrote on X. ‚ÄúI hold this as a possibility for America too. Can we disagree without hating our opponents? Can we restore civility and respect to public discourse? I think we can.‚Äù   RFK Jr. is the strongest of the third-party and independent candidates, and while he stands no chance of being elected, both the Biden and Trump campaigns fear he could siphon votes from them in key states in November. video_transcription: Breaking News, RFK Jr., nominated by President-elect Donald Trump to lead the Department of Health and Human Services, is taking aim at Big Pharma with a bold proposal‚Äîbanning TV drug ads. He argues these ads promote over-prescription, raise health care costs, and prioritize profit over patient health. Did you know the U.S. and New Zealand are the only countries that allow TV drug ads? Last year alone, Big Pharma spent $3 billion advertising popular drugs like Ozempic and Humira. Supporters say this ban could lower costs and put the focus back on doctor-patient relationships, but critics warn it could face legal challenges under the First Amendment, with ads being protected as free speech. What do you think? Should TV drug ads be banned, or is this too much of a stretch? Let's talk about it in the comments.

text: Cornel West is a legendary philosopher, author, and activist who has dedicated his life to fighting for justice and equality. From his powerful critiques of capitalism to his unwavering advocacy for marginalized communities, West's voice resonates with truth and compassion. According to West, a democratic individual is someone who actively engages in the democratic process, advocating for the rights and well-being of all members of society. This individual values inclusivity, fairness, and collective decision-making. On the other hand, a Socratic individual is one who possesses a commitment to truth-seeking, critical thinking, and intellectual honesty. Drawing from the teachings of the ancient Greek philosopher Socrates, West emphasizes the importance of self-examination, questioning assumptions, and engaging in meaningful dialogue to arrive at deeper understandings of ourselves and the world around us. In essence, West's notion of a democratic and Socratic individual calls for active citizenship, empathy, and intellectual curiosity as essential components of a just and flourishing society. video_transcription: Part of what it is to live behind the veil, to use W.E.B. Du Bois' great metaphor, the veil that divides America psychically, not just racially, not just the matters I said before. Tennessee Williams is on the blue side. Britney Spears, we have to debate about her. God bless and be with her. Clarence Thomas, we got to debate about that, brother. This is not a racial divide. It has to do with what kind of vision you have, what commitment you have, what orientation you have. Never allow anybody to pigeonhole you based on your race, gender or class. You're a human being who has choices that you can make if you have enough courage to think for yourself and love deep enough. But at this particular moment, who has the courage to say Saddam Hussein is a gangster now? And when the United States was in alliance with him, he was a gangster then. Who has the courage to say that bin Laden is a gangster now? And when he was in alliance with the United States, he was a gangster then. Who has the courage to say both in part created by the CIA and now wanted by the FBI? Meaning what? If you're going to talk about terrorists and gangsters and thugs, begin first with oneself, one's own thuggish dispositions, then look around in one's own context and neighborhood. Because I grew up with some thugs. I love them to death. They're just thugs. I knew that. Everybody knew that. And we brought some serious critique to bear on them because they did not contribute to the health of the community. To put it euphemistically. Then I look at our elites. What are their thuggish dispositions? What does it mean to have access to millions and millions of dollars when your workers' pensions are being sucked up and devoured? That's thuggish behavior. When I look at certain churches and mosques and synagogues and see these leaders in for the money rather than the rich, deep religious content of the way of life, that's thuggish behavior. When I look at certain portions of U.S. foreign policy, what went on in Guatemala in 1954, in Brazil in 1965, what went on in Iran in 1954. Overthrowing democracies in the name of American foreign policy, which claims to be concerned about democracies. That's thuggish behavior. No thuggish act justifies another thuggish act. Not at all. A lot of people say, oh, Brother West, you know, when you begin to talk this way, you sound anti-American. I say, I'm just trying to be Socratic and prophetic. And I happen to be a Christian, too. But we won't get into that today. And not only that, but you try to be consistent, thoroughly consistent. Same is true in the Middle East. No to thuggish behavior on behalf of Palestinians. No to thuggish behavior on the part of the Israelis. Killing of innocent people, suicide bombers, thuggish activity, subjugation, occupation of a people. Thuggish behavior. Why not just tell the truth across the board? To do what? To try to free people up so that a conversation can become more robust and uninhibited. And most importantly, so that that plain speaking that made Socrates so unpopular can become contagious so that his spirit can still live. Even given the death that occurred in 399 B.C. when the Athenian democracy put Socrates to death.

video_transcription: Joining me for their first joint television interview since announcing that ticket is Independent Presidential Candidate Dr. Cornel West and his Vice Presidential Nominee Dr. Malina Abdullah. Thank you both for being with us. Dr. West, I want to start with you. This is, as you noted, a history-making choice on your part, an all-African American ticket, but also a ticket that includes the first Muslim on a presidential ticket that was announced on Eid, the end of Ramadan. What message are you sending by doing that? First, I want to thank you for having both of us on. It's always a blessing to be on with my dear sister Malina. But no, I think both of us, we come from a great tradition of a great people who, in the face of hatred, terror, and trauma, produce love warriors, freedom fighters, and wounded healers. And both of us attempt to be true to that tradition. That's what I meant when I said put a smile on the face of Fannie Lou Hamer, and a smile on the face of Martin Luther King Jr., smile on the face of Harriet Tubman. So very much like the musicians, you know what I mean? That when Marvin and Tammy get together, or when Count Basie asks for Billie Holiday, it's a black ticket rooted in the best of a people, but it embraces everybody, because it's about justice across the board. It's about freedom across the board. Most importantly, it's about truth, because we've got a whole lot of lying, and hatred, and revenge in American politics. We provide an alternative vision and a different way of engaging politics. So I do have to ask you about the political realities that we're in. You know this as well as I do. Some of this polling is not good for you, Dr. West. It shows seven swing states that will decide the election. You are behind Robert Kennedy Jr. in all of them, the low single digits. The same is true in a national poll. The same is true even among independent voters, young voters, people who I think you would think are part of your constituency. Do you read that as a sign that there is not perhaps the appetite for what you are putting on the table? Well, we shall see. It has never looked good for anybody who has a deep love for black people, love for poor people, love for working people, to be up against the system. That's just the case, you know what I mean? You understand that, Trinidad, Brother Carlos, Sister June. We're going to keep loving our child, but it doesn't look good. Look at you now, sharp, on TV, Harvard trained. You never know. You got to keep loving, keep fighting, keep swinging. That's what this ticket is all about, and I'm blessed to be with my dear sister on it. So I want to ask Dr. Abdullah, you are a newcomer to the political sphere, and I want to ask you about some of your positions. You have tweeted in the past about supporting defund the police, which is something that I think perhaps some people in the Black Lives Matter movement support, but also this tweet from back in 2015, the KKK, the police, and government officials are one in the same. I wonder, do you stand by that comment? Absolutely, and thank you for having me. I want us to understand the history of policing in this country. And so Twitter doesn't allow you to give a whole history of policing in this country, but in a few sentences, we can just confirm that there is no historian that I've ever come in contact with who disputes the fact that policing in this country hails from slave catching. And so when we say that policing is, you know, the new millennial slave catching, we're not saying that we don't want public safety. We're saying we want real public safety where community is really centered, where black safety is centered, and we know that when black people are safe, we also create safety for everyone else. Dr. West, you talked about your campaign being about abolishing police brutality, poverty, and homelessness. Can you be specific, what are the policies behind those pretty big, lofty ideas? Well, one is that, you see, abolition is the fundamental theme of the Black Freedom Movement that embraces poor and working people across the board. Abolition of slavery, abolition of Jim Crow. I want abolition of poverty, I want the abolition of homelessness, I want the abolition of workers not gaining assets to wages so that the larger context of policing has to do with, we've got to make sure we don't have poor people in despair, we've got to make sure the young children have quality education, health care, and living wage, and safe community. So it goes hand in hand in that regard. But it's the ugly police brutality that we just saw in Mississippi with Brother Jenkins and Brother Parker. Thank God for Malik Shabazz and Brother Trent down there, the lawyers. What happened down there? These brothers are getting shot in the mouth. We see it over at Dexter Reed in Chicago. That's what we want to abolish in a fundamental way. But Dr. West, I think the question was, forgive me for interrupting, about policy solutions. You acknowledge, we acknowledge the problem. What is the solution in your mind? No, but abolition of policy, of poverty, is a policy. That's very important. Wages being high enough, quality education is a policy. And then we have police having, community having oversight of the police, and the police being accountable. That's why I mentioned Brother Jenkins and Brother Parker. Police must be accountable, but we have to understand policing in the context of the larger communal conditions, which have to do with too many poor people, not enough assets to education, not enough assets to health care. We have a lot to, a lot of issues on the table here in this election. One of the biggest ones right now is what's going on in Gaza, in the war over there. I know that you both support a ceasefire there. Well, not a ceasefire, end of occupation, end of the ceasefire in Palestine. Can I just ask you specifically about where we stand here today? Hamas, according to CNN's reporting, cannot assure Israel that it has 40 living hostages that are women, that are ill, that are elderly, out of the more than 100 that are still believed to be in Gaza. If they cannot do that, they don't know where they are, perhaps they can't guarantee that they are still alive. Should Hamas immediately release all of the hostages in exchange for a ceasefire that is desperately needed by the people of Gaza? No, we've got to look at the situation from the vantage point of the least of these, the 25th chapter of Matthew. There's 15,000 Palestinian children who've been murdered. That's all the more reason why there ought to be a ceasefire. It is possible for there to be a ceasefire tomorrow if Hamas would release all the hostages in their possession immediately. Should they not do that? No, no, the IDF is not gonna ceasefire just for releasing. They themselves have to stop the bombing. That's the deal that is on the table. And Hamas themselves say they can't assure them that they have 40 hostages. Each life is precious, Israeli or Palestinian or whatever, but it's the Palestinian lives that are being lost. We've got to start there. That's been part of the problem with Biden. That's been part of the problem with Schumer. They don't look at the situation from the vantage point of those who are suffering the most. They look at the- Dr. West, I mean, it does sound like you will not say that if Hamas were to just release the hostages in exchange for a ceasefire that they should do that. Do you believe that they should do that? One, I'm saying that Nathan Yahoo is not trustworthy. The IDF has engaged in terrorizing the Palestinians and terrorizing anybody is wrong, but the terrorizing that they are doing, it reaches the point of the crime of genocide. So for me, they have to stop the bombing. There is no responsibility in your mind for Hamas to get a ceasefire? Well, Hamas has responsibility, of course. They're part of the Palestinian community and Palestinian community has their own agreements and disagreements, but Hamas is not the culprit at all. It's the IDF and their terrorizing Palestinians. I want to go to Dr. Abdullah on this because in the early days just after this war began, shortly after October 7th, the Black Lives Matter chapter of Los Angeles, it's an organization that you founded and spent some time in, I believe at that time, wrote this on social media. When a people have been subject to decades of apartheid and unimaginable violence, their resistance must not be condemned but understood as a desperate act of self-defense. That sounds like a defense of Hamas. Is that what it was? That was a statement that was released not just by Black Lives Matter Los Angeles, but Black Lives Matter grassroots, which is all 33 on the ground chapters of Black Lives Matter. And we released it October 9th, which was two days after October 7th. So do you agree with that statement? Recognizing. Do you agree with that? Absolutely. I think it's really important to understand where uprisings come from, even when we may disagree with tactics that are used. This did not begin on October 7th. This began 75 years ago with the Nakba. And so to understand just one piece of what's happening gives us a complete lack of understanding. So we have to understand this, yes, as a desperate act. video_transcription: We know there are two main parties in American politics, but did you know there's another? The Green Party. Of these, one of the key pillars that could spark a change in votes for Greens comes from the issue of the Israel-Gaza conflict, with one poll showing Stein leading Harris among Muslim American voters in the key swing states of Michigan, Arizona and Wisconsin. The abandoned Harris protest group, which opposes the US's funding of Israel, has recently endorsed Stein and the Green Party. Jill Stein is the party's presidential nominee for the third consecutive election. In previous elections, third parties have provoked the scorn of the Democratic Party, who directly blamed Stein for taking votes away from Hillary Clinton and in the 2016 election, Donald Trump won. A similar fear is being cited now, with Democratic activists and pundits claiming that a vote for Stein only helps Trump and the Republicans. The Green Party faces a massive battle to gain influence in America's political system. However, Jill Stein could end up becoming a defining part of next month's election.

video_transcription: have the sickest population and it's because they're mass poisoning us. And so how do you stop that? It's very difficult to do it through legislation because when I brought the Monsanto cases, we had 40,000 clients who were home gardeners mainly who got non-Hodgkin's lymphoma from using Roundup, which the active ingredient of Roundup is a chemical called glyphosate. And everybody said, even if you can prove that glyphosate caused these cancer, you can never get rid of it because 95% of the herbicides in the world are without one Roundup and they own the corn industry, they own Cargill, they own Monsanto, the biggest corporations in the world, and they own the agricultural committees and it's impossible to challenge and they own the regulatory agency. Here's how we did it. We had 40,000 people who got home gardeners who got non-Hodgkin's lymphoma from using Roundup. We brought multi-district litigation against them. We had enough science by that time, about 15 or 20 studies that all said they were animal studies, epidemiological studies, clinical study, observational studies, bench trial studies, all of these different mishmash of studies that all said the same thing, that this causes non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. Once you get that critical mass of studies, you can surpass the threshold, that's called the Daubert threshold in federal courts where a federal judge, before he lets you go to a jury with a case in which you're saying a chemical exposure caused such and such an effect, he has to make an independent determination that sufficient science, a sufficient threshold of science, a critical mass of a whole different blend of studies is out there that supports this. That's called the Daubert threshold and we just surpassed that with Monsanto. Once we did that, we were able to go to court. The way that multi-district litigation works is you get a whole bunch of cases and then you try them one at a time until somebody says, The first case we tried in San Francisco, we won $289 million. The second case, and that was a gardener, a superintendent, school superintendent, African-American who had been forced against his will with a leaky backpack. He got non-Hodgkin's lymphoma all over his body. The second case we tried in Oakland, we won $89 million. The third case was a couple home gardeners that had been spraying together for years. First, their laboratory retriever who was with them every day in the garden died of non-Hodgkin's lymphoma. The two of them got it at the exact same time. We asked the jury in that case for a billion dollars and they came back with $2.2 billion. At that point, Monsanto came to the negotiating table and said, We're done. Let's settle this. They settled it for $13 billion and they agreed to take Roundup or to take glyphosate out of Roundup for home gardening purposes.
